China's state television on Thursday night broadcast a classic Chinese film featuring Chinese army's heroic roles in the Korean War (1950-1953), replacing the scheduled program about the ongoing Asian Film and TV Week, and later announced the screening of another military film on the same theme on Friday, prompting wide discussions online amid the simmering China-US trade warThe China Central Television (CCTV)'s movie channel CCTV-6 posted on its Weibo on Thursday night that classic war movie Heroic Sons and Daughters would be screened on 8:25 pm, and the previously scheduled red-carpet events of the Asian Film and TV Week would be delayed to 10:20 pm.Later, the channel posted another announcement saying that it would screen another military film Battle on Shangganling Mountain, depicting a major battle in North Korea, on Friday night. Both films featured the war to resist US aggression and aid Korea, as it is popularly called in China, and they were not listed on the channel's previous directory.The CCTV's posts received wide praises from Chinese netizens who believed they indicated China's firm position to the US amid the escalated trade war. Some even called for more patriotic programs and films to be screened to boost patriotism among the public. "We are not afraid of the US, not in the past, not today. Thumbs-up to the CCTV," commented one netizen. Some netizens even nicknamed CCTV-6 as the "sixth princesses" for it has always been sensitive on politics and hot news. Netizens found that CCTV-6 aired Les Miserables during the "yellow vest movement" in Paris in March, and aired the film Pearl Harbor when Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe visited the US in 2016.Global Times Chinese scientists design gene-editing tool using light to kill cancer cellsAbsence at PLA maritime parade will prevent US from learning about Chinese Navy: expertsChinese American organization condemns increasing racial profiling in US Actress Liu honored with Hollywood Walk of Fame starUnrealistic expectations thwart Chinese job recruitersDelegation of HUST attends alumni gala in Los Angeles